Please do a special on the new CA law banning the sale of puppy mill dogs. CA stores are still selling these dogs through loopholes and my parents unknowingly bought a dog from there. When they found out, they feel like there is nothing they can do about it as the contract is very odd. They also make it mandatory to get the dog cleared through a vet they chose for us. That vet hid things from us that a second vet not affiliated with the store shared with us. Please help spread the word. This chain, The Fancy Puppy is breaking the law through this loophole and are selling hundreds of puppy mill dogs a day in CA. I want to make sure that they are held accountable. The fine for breaking this law is so insignificant, a person needs to expose this! contact me for details of my parents case, as we have many details we can share with you.


Thank you for your time

snippet.textDisplay: I've stopped checking for Bill Maher and Jon Oliver to come back after their very long summer and holiday breaks.  Their extended absences have made them irrelevant, when all the other late-night comedians have stepped up and delivered regularly. Stephen Colbert and his team are there all the time, with very minimal break time for holidays and vacations.  Ditto for Seth Meyers, Trevor Noah, and Jimmy Kimmel. If a link for "Last Week Tonight" or "Real Time" happens to come across my screen, I may check it out.  But I'm done waiting and searching and hoping there will be a new episode after weeks and weeks of nada from them.

snippet.textDisplay: Dear John Oliver, There is no way to start this right in a way that it actually makes sense what I want to try here. I love your show, it makes me feel the same way about the world as I feel about my life when things go bad, I laugh about it. Well, I do have researched quite a bit about social media, beginning with censorship on a very visual level, particularly in art. Then it went over to research about the effects of social media and the use of technology in general, considering voices like Yuval Noah Harari, Simon Sinek, Robert Sapolsky and Tristan Harris. I know the world sinks in utter chaos and as you rightfully say, next year is gonna be even worse, but also social media has become so important as outlet of opinions, stories and news that I think the topic of censorship on a level of exactly those 3 things mentioned may be quite worth discussing too. I feel censorship on social media combines a lot of topics together, like the race for our attention to earn money with it and the effects on mental health and shaping of opinions in society that you guys would do the best job possible of putting it in a way no one else could. Considering all aspects and make it understandable for all. So this is what it is, a cry for help on an issue that millions are suffering from. A cry in a wast mass, like asking a question in a group chat. but maybe I'm lucky. otherwise I'm just happy to express my gratitude towards existing humans like you. thank you.

snippet.textDisplay:
I think a similar mentality pushes the phenomenon of "breaking news." I live in the Denver area, and months ago, we received a breaking news story about a helicopter that had crashed high atop a building, downtown.
They broke into our regularly scheduled broadcasts to tell us this happened, and then spent several minutes looking for more information, because 9/11 and all.
I thought, "9/11? Really? You folks are suggesting that the helicopter might have been hijacked by terrorists and now that building is in danger of coming down?"
Now, after several minutes, they found nothing, and this was the last I heard of it. It turns out, the helicopter crashed because the scheduled pilot lost control of it at the worst moment. For some reason, this news story could not wait for a regularly scheduled newscast. It absolutely had to be reported, right then, because 9/11 and all. 🤷
